    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b5d154a72a5086ef",
      "text": "# Case Example of Attribute Maps Based on Incomplete Data Matrices (Missing Data): “Poverty Map”\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bf438afa90d29a8f",
      "text": "It has turned out that the SOM is a very robust algorithm, compared with many other neural models. One of the frequently encountered problems in practical (especially statistical) applications is caused by missing data. However, if the number of attributes taken into account is appreciable, say, at least on the order of hundreds, an appreciable fraction of data may be missing without making the similarity comparison impossible.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "96371ba59479209c",
      "text": "To start with, it is advisable to normalize each attribute scale such that its variance taken over all the items is unity. Similarly one may subtract the mean from each attribute: thus the scales are said to be (0,1) -normalized.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "70eda5f1300a58fa",
      "text": "Comparison of an item with the codebook vectors is best made in the Euclidean metric, unless some better metric is deducible from the nature of the problem. Then, however, only the known components of x, and the corresponding components of each m_i, can be taken into account in the comparison: during this step the vectors are redimensioned correspondingly.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "baa24331f9aa3b5c",
      "text": "The data used in this case example were derived from the statistics published by World Bank [3.20]. We selected 39 indicators that somehow describe the poverty of the countries, or their citizens. All indicators are relative to population."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ad389abf0221bc0f",
      "text": "For 126 countries of the world listed, 12 or more indicator values of 39 possible ones were given to 78 countries and these countries were then taken to the data matrix used in training the SOM process. In Fig. 3.23, these countries are labeled by capital letters. For the countries labeled by lowercase symbols, more than 11 attribute values were missing, and they were mapped onto the SOM after training.\n"
    },
